text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eremophila mackinlayi was first formally described in 1864 by Victorian Government Botanist Ferdinand von Mueller in Fragmenta phytographiae Australiae. The specific epithet (mackinlayi) honours the explorer John McKinlay.Eremophila strongylophylla  is regarded as a synonym of  E. mackinlayi at the World Checklist of Selected Plant Families but is still treated as a species in its own right by the Western Australian HerbariumTwo subspecies are currently recognised:

E.mackinlayi F.Muell. subsp. mackinlayi has leaves which are elliptic, egg-shaped or almost circular and which are scattered along the branches;
E. mackinlayi subsp. spathulata Chinnock has leaves that are spoon-shaped, or egg-shaped with the narrow end towards the base, and which are clustered at the ends of the branches.
